### Complexity Analysis

Quick Sort is generally very efficient, but its performance depends on pivot selection:

**Time Complexity:**
- **Best Case: O(n log n)** — Occurs when the pivot divides the array into two equal halves
- **Average Case: O(n log n)** — Expected performance with random data
- **Worst Case: O(n²)** — Occurs when the pivot is always the smallest or largest element (e.g., already sorted array with first element as pivot)

**Space Complexity:**
- **O(log n)** — Due to the recursion stack in the best/average case
- **O(n)** — In the worst case when the recursion tree is skewed

**Advantages:**
- In-place sorting (requires only O(log n) extra space for recursion)
- Cache-efficient due to good locality of reference
- Generally faster than other O(n log n) algorithms in practice

**Disadvantages:**
- Worst-case time complexity of O(n²)
- Not stable (doesn't preserve the relative order of equal elements)
- Performance heavily depends on pivot selection

**Optimization Strategies:**
1. **Random pivot selection:** Helps avoid worst-case scenarios
2. **Median-of-three:** Choose pivot as median of first, middle, and last elements
3. **Hybrid approach:** Switch to insertion sort for small subarrays (< 10 elements)
4. **Three-way partitioning:** Efficient for arrays with many duplicate values
